    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's just frustrating because it feels like there's something extra taking most of my money before it even hits the loan itself. can you explain the specific formula used to calculate that monthly interest so i can see exactly how much is being taken out each time?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The formula for calculating the monthly interest is straightforward, though it can feel sneaky when you're deep in the debt cycle. You need to calculate the interest accrued for that specific month using the following structure: $\\text{Monthly Interest} = \\text{Current Principal Balance} \\times \\left( \\frac{\\text{Annual Interest Rate}}{12} \\right)$. That fraction, dividing the annual rate by 12, is what converts the yearly percentage into a monthly decimal rate. You then subtract that calculated interest from your fixed monthly payment to see what's left over to chip away at the principal. Seeing that number shrink month-to-month is the key to seeing the payoff happen!",
      "source": "target",
